responded: The root cause of the heap buffer overflow is in this code block:
```cpp
uint32_t iccOffset = 0;
while (iccOffset < 80 && iccOffset < chunkLength) {
    if (chunkData.pData_[iccOffset++] ==  0x00) {
        break;
    }
}
profileName_ = std::string(reinterpret_cast<char *>(chunkData.pData_), iccOffset-1);
++iccOffset; // +1 = 'compressed' flag
enforce(iccOffset <= chunkLength, Exiv2::kerCorruptedMetadata);
zlibToDataBuf(chunkData.pData_ + iccOffset, chunkLength - iccOffset, iccProfile_);
```
If the loop does not find a `0x00` byte within the first 80 bytes or before `chunkLength`, `iccOffset` will be incremented to a value that could be out of bounds (i.e., `iccOffset == chunkLength`), and then `iccOffset-1` will be used as the length for the string constructor, causing a read past the end of the buffer.

